FAQs    How do I know if I'm prepared to participate in the Committee process and apply this cycle?  Professional schools look for evidence that you can manage the challenges of their curriculum and will view your cumulative grade point average (GPA) and BCPM (Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Math) GPA as your way of demonstrating this. Other considerations include trends in your academic performance, the diversity and rigor of your courses, knowledge of the profession you seek to enter, and a demonstrated commitment to health care on an individual and/or societal level.   NYU's competitive candidates for allopathic medical schools traditionally earn a 3.6 GPA overall and in the sciences and earn a 32 on the MCAT entrance exam. NYU's competitive candidates for dental schools traditionally earn a 3.5 GPA overall and 3.4 GPA in the sciences; they also earn a 20 on the DAT. Academic standards vary from discipline to discipline and school to school. We encourage you to use the admissions materials in Preprofessional Advising Center's resource library to help you collect information about your programs of interest.   Students should only apply once and when their portfolio (grades, entrance exam scores, extra-curricular activities) is the strongest. Decisions about when to apply should result from a reflection of your academic record and accomplishments in respect to the admissions standards at your programs of interest. If you have any reservations or questions about applying, we recommend meeting with an advisor prior to submitting your Prehealth Committee Application. If you do delay applying, we recommend postponing your interview as well, until you can present a stronger record and we can write you a stronger letter.     I understand that NYU’s Committee Letter of Evaluation will evaluate and characterize my candidacy as reflected in my Declaration of Intent, Prehealth Committee Application, Committee Interview, and feedback from Committee members. The evaluation will be relative to the larger NYU applicant pool and the entrance standards of the professional schools I seek to enter.     Where can I learn more about the admissions' standards for students entering my profession?   Professional organizations publish aggregated applicant and matriculant data. We encourage you to review this information as you assess your application readiness and academic preparation:     American Association of Colleges of Osteopathic Medicine (AACOM)    American Association of Colleges of Pharmacy (AACP)    American Association of Colleges of Podiatric Medicine (AACPM)    American Dental Education Association (ADEA)    Association of American Medical Colleges (AAMC)    Association of American Veterinary Medical Colleges (AAVMC)    Association of Schools and Colleges of Optometry (ASCO)    Additional data can be found online and in the Preprofessional Advising Center's Resource Library.     I understand that some schools may require additional courses beyond the basic “ prehealth curriculum ,” and recognize that it is my responsibility to research and review entrance requirements and application deadlines of the schools to which I will apply.    I have self-assessed my application readiness based on the standards of the professional schools I seek to enter.     How does the Committee evaluate candidates?  NYU's Committee makes every effort to evaluate students in a holistic way. We account for:     Experiences: educational background, clinical work, research, community service, leadership, life experiences, "distances travelled"    Attributes: demographic profile, leadership skills, ability to work with and for people who may be very different from you, maturity, communication skills, fields of interest, intellectual curiosity    Metrics: grades, grade trends, academic rigor      This information is gleaned from the sources outlined in the Composition of the NYU Committee Letter of Evaluation section above.    Why does the Committee expect me to collect letters of recommendation?    Letters of recommendation are an important component of the application process. It is in your best interest to select writers who have observed your work, can attest to your abilities and strengths, and can appropriately assess your fit for your professional program and future occupation.   The Committee will reference and quote the content of these recommendations as a way of corroborating and underscoring elements of your candidacy. Unabridged copies of these letters will be attached as addenda to your Committee Letter when it is submitted to centralized application services and/or programs to which you apply.   It is important that you use good judgment when selecting recommendation writers. The Preprofessional Advising Center will serve as your letter repository, storing each recommendation for you as they arrive and for up to 7 years. Every recommendation that we receive on your behalf goes into your prehealth file and will move forward with your NYU Committee Letter. It is very important that you provide each writer with timely, accurate information and instructions that will allow him/her to fully support your application to health professional schools.    The Preprofessional Advising Center has developed the following webinar to assist you with the Letter of Recommendation collection process:       Click the picture to load the webinar        How do I know if the type of program I plan to apply to requires a Committee Letter?  Nearly all health professional schools strongly recommend that students obtain an institutional letter of evaluation (e.g. Committee Letter) if the service is available at his/her institution. However, some centralized application services and professional programs do not accommodate traditional NYU Committee Letters (           CASPA ,            SOPHAS , and       VMCAS ).  If you plan to apply to Physician Assistant, Public Health, and Veterinary programs that use these services, we ask that you consult with Preprofessional Advising Center staff before proceeding with the Committee process.     What should I expect from the Committee Interview?  Be prepared to discuss your educational and career path, and any of the information that you submitted as part of your Declaration of Intent and the Prehealth Committee Application. Please keep in mind that the interview is not an advising session. It is a professional interview that will influence the Committee Letter of Evaluation and will help YOU prepare for future admissions interviews. As such, please arrive on time, dressed professionally, and prepared to engage in a meaningful conversation.   The Wasserman Center offers in-person and web-based resources that can help you hone your interviewing skills so that you can put your best foot forward.     If I've already submitted a Committee Application and have been interviewed, do I need to do this again?  No, you do NOT need to complete a Committee Application or interview a second time. Declaration of Intent  Your Declaration of Intent is the first component of NYU’s Prehealth Committee process. The Declaration is designed to assist the Preprofessional Advising Center to accurately anticipate the number and variety of prehealth students who wish to participate in the 2014-2015 Prehealth Committee process. The goal of the Declaration is twofold:       The Preprofessional Advising Center will use students’ responses to gauge the number and needs of the students who wish to receive an institutional Committee Letter. This will allow our staff to efficiently manage students’ needs in the months ahead.        The Declaration is comprised of a series of questions that reveal your intentions and readiness to participate in the Committee process. We expect you to reflect and answer honestly when completing the form.       The Declaration of Intent is an electronic application that asks you to report basic identifying information about your prehealth interests and portfolio. All students are required to complete the Declaration in order to gain access to this cycle's Prehealth Committee Application. The Declaration will take no longer than 45 minutes to complete, but may be completed in more than one sitting once an initial Declaration is saved. You may retrieve your saved Declaration at any time by using your NYU ID (N#) and Declaration password . Applying to schools of the health professions is a weighty, detail-oriented undertaking. Students may begin the process as early as the fall semester of the junior year, if applying to begin health professional school directly after graduation. Those who decide to take a "glide year" between undergraduate and health professions school will begin the application process in the fall of senior year. Still others may return as alumni to begin the application process, utilizing the services offered by NYU’s Preprofessional Advising Center.   Participating in the NYU Committee process is the first of many steps that you will take towards admission into schools of the health professions. We ask that you read the following overview, reference our instructional webinars, and review the FAQs prior to submitting your Declaration of Intent and Prehealth Committee Application. You will be required to acknowledge your understanding of specific practices and procedures in order to submit your completed declaration of intent and application.    There are some professions and application services that do not expect or accept NYU Committee Letters. These programs are discussed in the FAQ section.     Purpose of the NYU Committee Letter of Evaluation  With few exceptions, schools of the health professions request that applicants have a letter of evaluation submitted on their behalf by the undergraduate institution where they completed the majority of the prehealth curriculum. At NYU we refer to this letter as the Committee Letter of Evaluation. The Committee Letter is designed to present you as a candidate by describing your academic record, engagement with the community, personal qualities, and demonstrated interest and commitment to healthcare. Health professional schools take these letters seriously in their overall evaluation of your application.   We recognize that the application process - from your participation in the Committee process to applying to schools of the health professions later this year - is a weighty exercise with many moving parts. The Preprofessional Advising Center has developed the Application Year Overview resource, available below, to clearly explain and describe the purpose and elements of NYU's Committee process. The webinar is one hour long and must be viewed by all students seeking a Prehealth Committee Letter of Evaluation.       Click the picture to load the webinar         I have viewed the Application Year Overview: Committee Process webinar in its entirety. (Please know this is a requirement for all students applying to receive a Prehealth Committee Letter of Evaluation.)      Composition of the NYU Committee Letter of Evaluation  The content of the Committee Letter is based on several sources:     Outside letters of recommendation    Declaration of Intent:         Autobiographical data      Professional Goals      Use of Advising Resources        Prehealth Committee Application:         Academic Achievements      Reflection statements      Preprofessional preparation (e.g. work and activities)        Committee Interview: A one-on-one interview with a Committee member    Committee Review: Discussion by Committee members regarding individual applicants’ qualifications.    A review of these materials and interactions allows us to write a personalized, thorough, and reliable letter that evaluates your readiness for professional school.   Preprofessional advisors will review your Committee Application in its entirety and, when preparing your Committee Letter of Evaluation, may choose to incorporate personal information you have provided in your reflections statements, autobiographical information, and your interview.   A late, rushed, or incomplete application does not make a good impression on either the Committee or on the health professional schools to which you are applying. We encourage you to take your time when completing the Prehealth Committee Application so that you can provide the Committee with thoughtful, authentic, and comprehensive responses. FAQs    How do I know if I'm prepared to participate in the Committee process and apply this cycle?  Professional schools look for evidence that you can manage the challenges of their curriculum and will view your cumulative grade point average (GPA) and BCPM (Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Math) GPA as your way of demonstrating this. Other considerations include trends in your academic performance, the diversity and rigor of your courses, knowledge of the profession you seek to enter, and a demonstrated commitment to health care on an individual and/or societal level.   NYU's competitive candidates for allopathic medical schools traditionally earn a 3.6 GPA overall and in the sciences and earn a 32 on the MCAT entrance exam. NYU's competitive candidates for dental schools traditionally earn a 3.5 GPA overall and 3.4 GPA in the sciences; they also earn a 20 on the DAT. Academic standards vary from discipline to discipline and school to school. We encourage you to use the admissions materials in Preprofessional Advising Center's resource library to help you collect information about your programs of interest.   Students should only apply once and when their portfolio (grades, entrance exam scores, extra-curricular activities) is the strongest. Decisions about when to apply should result from a reflection of your academic record and accomplishments in respect to the admissions standards at your programs of interest. If you have any reservations or questions about applying, we recommend meeting with an advisor prior to submitting your Prehealth Committee Application. If you do delay applying, we recommend postponing your interview as well, until you can present a stronger record and we can write you a stronger letter.     I understand that NYU’s Committee Letter of Evaluation will evaluate and characterize my candidacy as reflected in my Declaration of Intent, Prehealth Committee Application, Committee Interview, and feedback from Committee members. The evaluation will be relative to the larger NYU applicant pool and the entrance standards of the professional schools I seek to enter.     Where can I learn more about the admissions' standards for students entering my profession?   Professional organizations publish aggregated applicant and matriculant data. We encourage you to review this information as you assess your application readiness and academic preparation:     American Association of Colleges of Osteopathic Medicine (AACOM)    American Association of Colleges of Pharmacy (AACP)    American Association of Colleges of Podiatric Medicine (AACPM)    American Dental Education Association (ADEA)    Association of American Medical Colleges (AAMC)    Association of American Veterinary Medical Colleges (AAVMC)    Association of Schools and Colleges of Optometry (ASCO)    Additional data can be found online and in the Preprofessional Advising Center's Resource Library.     I understand that some schools may require additional courses beyond the basic “ prehealth curriculum ,” and recognize that it is my responsibility to research and review entrance requirements and application deadlines of the schools to which I will apply.    I have self-assessed my application readiness based on the standards of the professional schools I seek to enter.     How does the Committee evaluate candidates?  NYU's Committee makes every effort to evaluate students in a holistic way. We account for:     Experiences: educational background, clinical work, research, community service, leadership, life experiences, "distances travelled"    Attributes: demographic profile, leadership skills, ability to work with and for people who may be very different from you, maturity, communication skills, fields of interest, intellectual curiosity    Metrics: grades, grade trends, academic rigor      This information is gleaned from the sources outlined in the Composition of the NYU Committee Letter of Evaluation section above.    Why does the Committee expect me to collect letters of recommendation?    Letters of recommendation are an important component of the application process. It is in your best interest to select writers who have observed your work, can attest to your abilities and strengths, and can appropriately assess your fit for your professional program and future occupation.   The Committee will reference and quote the content of these recommendations as a way of corroborating and underscoring elements of your candidacy. Unabridged copies of these letters will be attached as addenda to your Committee Letter when it is submitted to centralized application services and/or programs to which you apply.   It is important that you use good judgment when selecting recommendation writers. The Preprofessional Advising Center will serve as your letter repository, storing each recommendation for you as they arrive and for up to 7 years. Every recommendation that we receive on your behalf goes into your prehealth file and will move forward with your NYU Committee Letter. It is very important that you provide each writer with timely, accurate information and instructions that will allow him/her to fully support your application to health professional schools.    The Preprofessional Advising Center has developed the following webinar to assist you with the Letter of Recommendation collection process:       Click the picture to load the webinar        How do I know if the type of program I plan to apply to requires a Committee Letter?  Nearly all health professional schools strongly recommend that students obtain an institutional letter of evaluation (e.g. Committee Letter) if the service is available at his/her institution. However, some centralized application services and professional programs do not accommodate traditional NYU Committee Letters (           CASPA ,            SOPHAS , and       VMCAS ).  If you plan to apply to Physician Assistant, Public Health, and Veterinary programs that use these services, we ask that you consult with Preprofessional Advising Center staff before proceeding with the Committee process.     What should I expect from the Committee Interview?  Be prepared to discuss your educational and career path, and any of the information that you submitted as part of your Declaration of Intent and the Prehealth Committee Application. Please keep in mind that the interview is not an advising session. It is a professional interview that will influence the Committee Letter of Evaluation and will help YOU prepare for future admissions interviews. As such, please arrive on time, dressed professionally, and prepared to engage in a meaningful conversation.   The Wasserman Center offers in-person and web-based resources that can help you hone your interviewing skills so that you can put your best foot forward.     If I've already submitted a Committee Application and have been interviewed, do I need to do this again?  No, you do NOT need to complete a Committee Application or interview a second time. Please submit all updates to our office no later than May 31, 2015. Yes, I am a first-time applicant who has never completed the Committee Application or had a Committee Interview          Students should complete the Prehealth Committee Application and participate in the Prehealth Committee Interview during the academic year immediately proceeding their intended summer application to health professional schools.     For example: Students who intend to apply to schools of the health professions during the summer of 2015 must complete the Committee Application in the fall of 2014 and interview with the Committee during the spring of 2015.     It is in your best interest to align these processes to prevent the need for future Committee updates. More importantly, however, you want to present the most refined version of your preprofessional portfolio (e.g. academic performance, entrance exam scores, co-curricular activities, and personal strengths). Committee members will be evaluating you on all of these dimensions; we urge you to thoughtfully consider the impressions the Committee will formulate based on your present portfolio.             Yes, but I completed a Committee Application in the past but did not have a Committee Interview          If you completed a Committee Application in the past but never interviewed with a member of the Committee, we ask that you submit a new Committee Application. Yes, but I completed a Committee Application AND Committee Interview in the past          If you have already interviewed with our office in the past, then you DO NOT need to complete a new Committee Application or have a second Committee Interview. March 15 is the recommended submission deadline for applicants to Postbaccalaureate/SMP programs, but it is your responsibility to research precise application deadlines for your programs of interest. Please bear in mind that it takes the Committee four weeks to send your composite NYU Committee Letter, of which LORs are a significant part, to your programs of interest.      We strongly advise at least one letter from a science professor and one letter from a professor in your major, but other professors, research supervisors, health professionals, etc. may write on your behalf as well. Three to five letters is sufficient.      Select writers who have observed your work, can attest to your abilities and strengths, and can appropriately assess your fit for your professional program and future occupation. Review the Letter of Recommendation webinar for suggestions and reminders about procedures.      Letters submitted to the Preprofessional Advising Center can only be used for the express purpose of applying to professional programs.      We will not accept or send outside letters of recommendation once we have sent your Committee Letter to application services/programs.                Letters of Recommendation: Documenting your Writers & Monitoring Receipt      The Preprofessional Advising Center has created an online letter of recommendation system, embedded in your Committee Application, that enables you to manage your letters of recommendation.       Please follow the steps below:          Report the information about your prospective writers in the space provided below. While 3-5 recommendations are suggested, you may include up to 10 individual writers.   When a letter is received, you will see a icon to let you know it has arrived. An email will also be sent to your NYU email address to alert you of a letter’s arrival. It is your responsibility to track the receipt of your letters by monitoring your email and completed Committee Application.                   ALERT: We will only be able to alert you about a letter's receipt if the letter author is listed in your Committee Application.                       It is your responsibility to update your list of writers in your Committee Application. While we encourage all applicants to be thoughtful and discerning about their recommendations from the start, we understand that not everyone you ask will be able to produce a recommendation. As soon as you learn that a writer will no longer be supplying a recommendation, log-in to your Committee Application and remove his/her name from your list.             Your Committee Letter cannot be finalized until the Preprofessional Advising Center is in receipt of all anticipated letters of recommendation. Do not request the transmission of your Committee Letter if you have letters of recommendations outstanding. We ask that you consider the following when deciding whether or not to waive your access to your Committee Letter:           The Family Education Rights and Privacy Act of 1974 (FERPA) gives applicants the right to access letters of evaluation unless they choose to waive their right of inspection and review. The Committee will note your waiver decision in your Committee Letter. By not waiving your rights, our Committee will only provide a factual account of your performance and will not include evaluative comments. Admissions personnel value and expect our Committee's commentary, and professional programs may interpret the Committee Letter as more honest and candid if you waive your right to see it. If you decide not to waive your right, then you may be asked to explain the reasons for your choice during an interview.
